  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering practices existed in ancient civilizations\n- Emerged more formally in response to organized crime in the early 20th century\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislative effort to combat money laundering\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large cash transactions\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- Introduced international standards for criminalizing money laundering\n- Encouraged global cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n4. Major Expansion:\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Made money laundering a federal crime in the US\n- Created comprehensive legal framework for prosecuting financial crimes\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards and recommendations\n- Promoted consistent global approaches to combating money laundering\n\n6. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) increased regulatory requirements\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Expanded scope of anti-money laundering regulations\n\nThis progression reflects increasing global recognition of money laundering as a significant financial and criminal challenge.",
